      "author": "ryanravn",
      "description": "## Fix: encrypted libraries are no longer silently un-encrypted on first sync\n\nIn 0.3.9 and earlier, the first sync against an encrypted Seafile library would corrupt it: the plugin uploaded commits without the encryption metadata fields, and the server uses the head commit to determine encryption status, so the library flipped to \\`encrypted: false\\` on the server. Any blocks already encrypted on disk became unreadable through the API.\n\n0.3.10 includes:\n- \\`encrypted: \"true\"\\`, \\`enc_version\\`, \\`magic\\`, \\`key\\`, and (when applicable) \\`salt\\` in uploaded commits when syncing to an encrypted library.\n- Uses the correct field name \\`key\\` for the wrapped block key (Seafile's wire format uses \\`key\\` in commit JSON, even though the same value is exposed as \\`random_key\\` on \\`/download-info/\\`).\n\nVerified live against a Seafile server: a fresh encrypted library remains \\`encrypted: true\\` after a patched sync, where 0.3.9 would have flipped it to \\`encrypted: false\\`.\n\n**Caveat for existing users:** if any of your previously-encrypted libraries were already corrupted by 0.3.9 (or earlier), they cannot be recovered. The head commit on the server lost the encryption metadata. Create a fresh encrypted library and move files into it. Verify with \\`/api/v2.1/repos/\\` — if it reports \\`encrypted: false\\` for a library you thought was encrypted, that's the symptom.",
      "downloadCount": 28,
